      "score": 41,
      "comments": 3,
      "author": "rcalixte",
      "published": "2026-05-25T00:35:59Z",
      "bullets": [
        "Generative AI slop poisons public web scraping data, creating model collapse feedback loops that degrade future LLM training quality.",
        "Unchecked LLM-generated code floods repositories like GitHub, increasing technical debt, security vulnerabilities, and package maintenance overhead.",
        "Search engine degradation and AI-generated SEO spam force engineers to rely on curated, closed developer communities for reliable technical information."
      ]
    },
    {
      "source": "lobsters",
      "subsource": "lobste.rs/security",
      "category": "security",
      "title": "How my minimal, memory-safe Go rsync steers clear of vulnerabilities",
      "url": "https://michael.stapelberg.ch/posts/2026-05-24-minimal-memory-safe-go-rsync-vulns/",
      "discuss_url": "https://lobste.rs/s/5y9u93",
      "score": 66,
      "comments": 6,
      "author": "stapelberg",
      "published": "2026-05-24T14:38:34Z",
      "bullets": [
        "Replacing legacy C rsync with Go eliminates common memory-safety vulnerabilities like buffer overflows, double-frees, and out-of-bounds pointer arithmetic.",
        "A minimal feature set dramatically reduces the attack surface compared to legacy rsync, eliminating complex, vulnerable protocol parsing logic.",
        "Using Go's standard library path sanitization mitigates classic rsync directory traversal exploits during remote file synchronization."
      ]
    },
